When we’re struggling inside the hurt position of un-initiated mentee, it’s easy to feel entitled towards our mentors.

“You’re supposed to make everything right for me.”

“You’re supposed to make me feel better.”

“You’re supposed to guide the way, impeccably.”

“You’re supposed to tuck me in and kiss my forehead goodnight when I’m feeling sad or scared.”

But the inconvenient honest truth is our greatest mentors are not our mothers, not our saviors, and not superhuman.

And? They’re not supposed to be.

They are our teachers.

Sometimes through their words.

Sometimes through their integrity.

And sometimes, disappointingly, through their shortfalls, flaws, and the things we discover about our own values and visions, in contrast to who they show themselves to be.

Of course, none of this is easy.

It’s not easy to come into the truth of who and how you want to be via the pain you’ve experienced with another.

It’s not easy to say, “They don’t owe me perfection, retribution, or even ongoing relations. They don’t owe me anything. The lessons I gain from this are mine and mine alone to excavate.”

And yes, deep (or mild) injustice can happen in any relational dynamic, including mentor / mentee. I’ve heard just about as many horror stories as you can imagine.

In more cases than not though, justice hasn’t been served via a tit-for-tat balancing of the scales. (I know, I know. You can hate me for saying it if you wanna.)

Refunds? Apologies? Restorative relational processes? They happen sometimes, sure.

But more often, justice is served by moving on.

By becoming bigger and clearer in your own leadership and power.

By taking responsibility for your part in the relational dance, and deciding to clean up your side of the street.

By forgiving yourself for any susceptibility or incongruence you embodied, any piece you contributed to the dramatic puzzle you found yourself in… and sometimes (when the time is right) maybe even forgiving the other, too.

By finding yourself in a new circle of belonging, more coherent and aligned to the current you, more resonant and right-fit for this next stage of life.

This was my most shared & saved post of 2022. And I’m kind of surprised… but also not totally.

Raise your hand if in the last few years you’ve been more sensitive to the potential to harm another. 🙋‍♀️

Now raise your hand if you’ve also been more sensitive to the potential of being harmed. 🙋‍♀️

I think in a culture that is ill-equipped to navigate differences (of opinion, communication styles, backgrounds, etc) — as well as in a culture that has deeply toxic systems — it’s super easy to outsource our hurts onto individuals. To jump to conclusions and vilify. (Others, or even ourselves.)

It’s also easy to reinvent harmful systems in our businesses.

And it’s hard, I mean really hard…

❤️To hold onto each other’s humanity amidst conflict.

❤️To take responsibility for our part in challenging situations.

❤️To ask questions before making accusations.

❤️To take responsibility when you *have* messed up… without spiraling into over-compensating shame.

❤️To be honest about your feelings—on either side of a conflict—rather than coalesce to another’s perspective.

❤️To accept disagreement or even hurt without calling it harm.

❤️To build something even 5% more liberatory and loving than whatever culture you grew up in.

But I think this is our edge as a human family these days. Listening. Nuance. Negotiating difference without attacking or collapsing.

What do you think?🔥

I went home to Maryland by myself this past 10 days. My mom kept whispering, “this is the last time you’ll be here all by yourself!“ As in, from this point on, I’ll forever (or at least for a long ass while) be accompanied by a little gremlin companion or two. 

It was the sweetest trip. No fights. No stress. Loads of television. Just the right amount of winter walks. And a warm embrace of my liminal growing body by my oldest friends and family.

I’m back in California now, all fucked up about living so far away from my parents, and also so glad to be snuggled up close with my two loves.

Not many more months with just the three of us. 

The baby kicks constantly now. In the morning when Seann wakes me up with kisses and sneaky hands, I pull his palm to the bottom of my belly, and whisper, “say good morning to the baby, too.” He crawls down to my womb, lips right on top of my skin, and whispers the softest sing song hellos. Then travels even further down to say good morning to the rest of me.

I have no idea who we’ll be this time next year. Morning sensual hellos? Slow Saturdays with nowhere to go? Rumors have it, unlikely. But I’m so glad we’re here now. Figuring out how to love each other wildly in the mystery.

For just a tad bit of historical context —

I grew up in an incredibly political & intellectual place (suburbs of DC). A place that was deeply diverse on many axis — race, class, religion, nationality, and also yes, political ideology.

I was raised in a culture that encouraged debate, dialogue *and* diplomacy.

And as a result, I was friends with people who loved Kenny Chesney, and friends with people who loved Baltimore Club. Friends with people who believed that Jesus saves, and friends with people who believed science is God.

Disagreeing and simultaneously remaining in relationship is not a sin.

It’s humanizing.

Bad decision: refund a half million dollars.

Bad decision: change careers 15 years in when you have mastery and an epic reputation.

Bad decision: come all the way out of every closet you’ve been hiding in.

Bad decision: bank on getting paid as an artist.

Bad decision: leave the safe but not-quite-right relationship. When you’re in your mid-30s and wanna have kids.

Bad decision: date someone twice your age.

Bad decision: tell on yourself about your secret addiction.

Bad decision: tell the customer they’re wrong.

Bad decision: slow down in the dead of winter.

Bad decision: live according to your body’s pace as opposed to the pace of capitalism.

What if the “bad” decision is actually the BEST decision? If you can muster the courage to honor your gut? If you can let the fall out burn away like sacred flame?

Tell me, what “bad” decisions have you made that changed everything for the better? I wanna hear, brazen one. 👇🏻🔥🫦

1. The mornings when I wake before Seann & use all my might to crawl over my mountainous pregnancy pillow only to reach the warm river of relief that is skin-to-skin snuggling with my all-in honey.

2. The muscle memory of his half-asleep strong-soft finger pads reaching for the places on my body that always always melt me.

3. That singular rule we made around our sex life that led to almost daily intimacy… and way more emotional closeness. 

4. That I dared to do less. Way way less. Stopped earning much money at all. Leaned into the sense in my body (over the panic in my mind) that when it’s truly time, the next divine call will rise. And until then, this radically internal creation process is enough.

5. That we opted out of an expensive wedding for the sake of a half a year together raising this little babe like he’s the most important thing there is. (#intimatehouseweddingFTW)

6. That we were scared. And grieving the end of our maiden/prince eras. And swan dove into the dark together, anyway.

7. Hard as it was, that I listened to the call of my body over the compulsion of capitalism. I slept til 9am. Made bone broth twice a week. Begrudgingly went to prenatal yoga. Walked rajah like some kind of religion. Sucked c*ck like a sacred mission. Because money can’t buy back this time. And ambition is always lurking like an ex lover. Just a quick call away. But not today. Today, I have my Beloveds. No need to hustle them away.

“It is much better to prepare yourself for change than to walk along the fault line pretending all is well.” - @kim_krans, the Wild Unknown Archetypes Guidebook.

If I am amidst the unavoidable change from Maiden to Mother, then to prepare myself for change is to ask myself, “WHERE ARE MY SUPPORTS?”

You think becoming Mother is about becoming everything for others. 

But how can you be anything for another without having something true and nourishing to offer?

Yes, I am called to become BIGGER. To grow & hold new life inside my body. Stretch my skin. Double my blood. Give of my calcium. 

So I must devour more flesh and fat. Lather more lotion on the cracks of my expansion. Feed on more breath & sweat in order to offer more truly living love.

Truly living love. That. That is what I am called to. A give and take. Not some fake homemaker version of ever expendable overflow.

It is hard to heed the needs of the Mother the when the Mother is designed to feed the needs of all the others.

But it is THE call. The dare. The defiant wisest way.

Day by day. I am getting bigger. I am insisting on more. I am resisting the lie of the martyred needless mother. I am smothering myself in care.

This does not come easy for me. I am not yet nourished to the bone. Which is why I make these little star charts. Tiny trackers of possibility. Visible reminders of deep intention. 

I am practicing. And practice is the promise of love.

Under tit rash. 23% nauseous almost always. Random bouts of 4 days in a row of crying. No clue about babies or how to care for them, aside from instincts. But my cousin Holly on call, thank goddess.

Hips that spread. A mouth that moans. A mind that knows the difference between extreme discomfort and actual danger. Find a prayer. Chant it in your mind. Steady surrender until you cross the mountain pass.

His soft green eyes. Our ever deepening devotion. Sass that says exactly what she wants. Love that fetches a zillion cups of water.

Existential isolation. The most loyal friends on earth. My dad’s adorable Blessing Way ideas text. “He just made up a ritual.” Seann’s jaw dropped, smiling awe, over how much my parents love me.

Every Jewish not-quite-yet and also always-have-been kin that are showing up like fleshy miracles to bring together our rites of passage. Parenthood. Matrimony. The rabbi & the erotic pastry chef. The networker & the jester. The village we knew was here. The opaque fear starting to clear.

Giving up old ambitions. Giving over old patterns. Giving in to amorphous timing. One clear calling: become family. Everything else? Fall away. Fall away for now.

The neighbor kids squealing. The open windows. The cool breeze. The first draft of our vows in pink gel pen on a random piece of paper. 

“We’re so excited to meet you baby!” & hands rubbing my teeming belly, in between the deep serious inquiry of what marriage means to us.

“What could break the spell of marriage for you?”
“Dishonesty. And you?”
“Meanness.”

The tears that fall from both our eyes at different times, for the same reason:

We will break this thing. Surely. But we will put it back together however many times it takes.

No bravado. No performed faith in our love. Just deep belly trust & whole hearted knowing. 

We. Want. This.
All of it. 
Every single messy beautiful bit.

This little mystery child who’s turning me into a primordial goddess. You know, the every day kind who’s been carved into stone since the beginning of time, billowing over & out. Shameless. She’s often pictured squatting with no smile on her face, just an unerasable knowing that she is now doing her part in the circle of life. Tied to a mystery child. 

Pump your blood, your fat, the wildness at the core of your bones, she whispers. Give it all over. But be sure to devour even more than you offer. You are here to glow while you grow, not wither.

I’m going to a potluck tonight dressed in a shirt that doesn’t really fit. Not that fitting into my clothes has ever really been my thing. But there will be new people at this crowded table & tits out will be my first impression. Overflowing. Growing, glowing, owning the primordial goddess. 

Don’t you wish this was a modern precedent? For women to be so full of themselves, together? Unaware that they were ever socialized to be anything other than big?

I wish you would tell me your uncouth thoughts. I wish you would dare your lover to not so much as look at another for one whole night—just for fun. I wish you would come to my kitchen table undone with all your ugly gory glorious bits of unfinished business & say, “I don’t want your advice. Just a kiss on the forehead & a promise that I’ll be okay.” I wish I had my old record player & all my moms old records that I left with Jen 10 years ago, so when you come, I respond, no prob. Go pick your favorite album. Let’s dance with the twinkle lights in the living room. Or you can sit on the couch and cry. Either way.

Whoever taught us that perfect is the path to belonging was a tiny-minded liar. We know bigger & better. We know growling wailing orgasms & the smell of stress at the end of the day. We know how to say, no matter. Come as you are. Whole & dirty. Squat & get ready. One day, you’ll birth yourself anew. But who cares when. Just right now, spilling over & out is enough.

If comfort is beginning to feel like a big ass puff jacket in the middle of summer, like an encumbering layer of protection that’s torturing you to wear, I dare you to get bare. Strip down to the raw flesh of your truest story. The discomfort of nudity doesn’t last forever. Soon enough, a first follower catches on and strips down, too. And there you both are, in the mess of your flabby magical truth, shaky but free. Less concerned with the comfort of the ones who never dare to bare themselves open in the sunlight, vulnerable and alive. More connected to the kin who sing the praises of truth louder than the praises of acceptability.

It was Oct 2021. We were high in a hot tub on Tourmaline Street, and I painted a picture of us doing the work together to be in service to clean water on planet earth for 500 years to come. 

In that moment, he got a vision of a light-filled path in a forest opening, and us walking it together until we were old. 

I’m a hardcore psychic—the kind of person who’s super difficult to surprise. So he thought, this is my chance! I can surprise her by surprising myself. I can ask her to marry me right here and now.

Except when he was giving his preamble to those Big Four Words, I saw an image in my minds eye of two golden strands twisting together and forming a ring. 

Is he gonna ask me to marry him right now? I thought. But he doesn’t have a ring…

And then it happened.

Absolutely. Yes. A million times yes. That was my response.

In the coming year, we went on to propose to one another at least four more times. In the bedroom. On the beach with our parents as witnesses. With a ring for me. And then a ring for him.

Every time: Absolutely. Yes. A millions times yes.

This isn’t my first marriage. Once upon a time, I was young and in love at 23, and then young and divorced at 25.

For a while during this second engagement, I played with the idea of *staying engaged* rather than getting married. I worried that the spell of the institution would crumble our devotion, make us lazy or entitled, trapped or fidgety.

I’m sure we’ll get to those places eventually. A lifetime’s a long time to feel all the feelings.

But there’s no one I’d rather face everything hard and beautiful and stretchy and real with than him.

Because he really is my best friend.

The rabbi, in our premarital counseling the other day, asked us, “so what do you like to do for fun?”

“Rituals” we both responded 😂

I have no idea where life will take us, but I know we’ll be casting spells and counting weeks by sabbath candles. I know we’ll be burning old contracts and burying outdated identities. I know we’ll be planting hopeful seeds and worshiping the panther black dark of the great mystery. And cackling. And sweating under the sheets. And holding each other tight through it all.
Full moon mood. 🌕❤️‍🔥

I don’t know about you (other humans who’ve traveled this dismantling journey into Mother), but for me, this year+ labyrinth has been fucking confusing. Disorienting. On some days, a total drag. On other days, a sacred, exciting dance with the mystery.

The closer I get to birthing our baby, the fewer people, practices and priorities get to come along with me.

Simple, simple. Everything wants to boil down to the ground. 

Flesh. Love. Spirit. 

What does my body need? 
What does my partnership need?

I didn’t want a time limit.

April 28th. The night I went into labor. We drove out to Doran Beach and I waddled down the shore and we threw the ball for Rajah and we knew (and also had no real clue) just how much everything was about to change.

It’s been 3 months since that day.

They always talk about how old the baby is, but for your first baby, it’s also how old you are as Mother, he is as Father, and together, you are as Parents.

We count it like a celebration… 6 weeks! 3 months! 1 year! Happy happy! Without acknowledging it’s also the anniversary of a death. Late night restaurants and sex in the morning. Spliffs whenever and spontaneous trips out of town. 

It’s the death of you at the center of your own universe. The initiation into decentering. Not as a forever practice. But as an absolute necessity in the beginning, little babe depending on you so severely.

We’re 3 months old now, all of us. Celebrating our capacity. Grieving the cost. Celebrating our healthy baby. Grieving our old bodies. Celebrating how relatively well we’re juggling the immense task of loving this child, and each other, and ourselves. Grieving how hard it is on so little sleep, with so little relief. Celebrating our teamwork. Grieving our spark.

The ‘we’ that has been has come to an end. We’re no longer just a couple, and never again will be. We’re a family. With the needs and complexities, joys and travesties that come along with it. Building a whole new ‘we’ one week at a time. Gently.

Simultaneously celebrating and grieving the new life we’re stretching into, the old life we’re offering thanks to.

And it feels important the name. The real both/and. The birth and the death. The beginning and end.

Phew. 3 months in.
